  <!-- Guide Tab -->
  <div id="guide-tab" class="tab-content active">

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üåê</span>
        Can Non-U.S. Residents Form Delaware C-Corporations?
      </h2>

      <p><strong>Yes‚Äîabsolutely.</strong> Delaware does not require shareholders, directors, or officers to be U.S. citizens or residents. Any individual or entity worldwide can form and own a Delaware C-Corporation. The only Delaware requirement is a registered agent with a physical Delaware address.</p>

      <p>However, forming a Delaware C-Corp as a non-resident comes with important considerations:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>U.S. Federal Tax:</strong> Your Delaware C-Corp is a U.S. taxpayer (21% corporate rate on worldwide income)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Dividend Withholding:</strong> 30% U.S. withholding on dividends to foreign shareholders (reduced by treaty)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Banking & KYC:</strong> U.S. banks require extensive documentation; fintech platforms more accessible</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Home Country Tax:</strong> You may also owe tax in your country of residence (CFC rules, worldwide income)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>VC/Investor Standard:</strong> Delaware C-Corp is the expected structure for raising U.S. venture capital</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚ö†Ô∏è Critical Disclaimer</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">This guide provides <strong>general educational information</strong>, not legal or tax advice. Cross-border corporate structures involve complex U.S. federal tax, treaty analysis, and home-country tax considerations. <strong>Always consult with both a U.S. CPA/international tax attorney AND a tax advisor in your home country</strong> before incorporating. Mistakes can result in double taxation, withholding penalties, or unexpected tax liabilities.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="status-badge">Updated: March 2025</div>
      <div class="alert-box alert-info">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üí° 2025 BOI/CTA Status for C-Corporations</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">As of March 2025, FinCEN's <strong>interim rule</strong> limits Beneficial Ownership Information (BOI) reporting to <strong>foreign reporting companies</strong> only. A Delaware-formed C-Corporation (domestic entity) is currently <strong>exempt from BOI filing</strong>. However, foreign entities registered to do business in the U.S. must file. This is an interim rule subject to future changes‚Äîmonitor FinCEN.gov for updates.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Who Should Consider -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üë•</span>
        Who Should Consider a Delaware C-Corporation?
      </h2>

      <p>Delaware C-Corps work well for specific non-resident scenarios where you need institutional-grade corporate structure, equity fundraising capability, or sophisticated cap table management:</p>

      <div class="persona-grid">
        <div class="persona-card">
          <span class="persona-icon">üöÄ</span>
          <h3 class="persona-title">SaaS & Tech Founders</h3>
          <p class="persona-desc">Building software products with U.S. customers, planning to raise U.S. venture capital, or targeting acquisition by U.S. tech companies. Need stock option plans and VC-compatible structure.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="persona-card">
          <span class="persona-icon">üíº</span>
          <h3 class="persona-title">Foreign Holding Companies</h3>
          <p class="persona-desc">EU/UK/Canada parent company using Delaware C-Corp as U.S. operating subsidiary for sales, distribution, or market presence. Common for cross-border group structures.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="persona-card">
          <span class="persona-icon">üéØ</span>
          <h3 class="persona-title">Dev Shops & Agencies</h3>
          <p class="persona-desc">Development studios or agencies wanting to offer equity to team members, structure for future sale, or work with U.S. enterprise clients who require corporate entities.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="persona-card">
          <span class="persona-icon">üìà</span>
          <h3 class="persona-title">Investment Vehicles</h3>
          <p class="persona-desc">Non-resident angels, micro-funds, or rolling funds using Delaware C-Corp to hold U.S. startup equity stakes. Provides structure for syndication and eventual exits.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="persona-card">
          <span class="persona-icon">üè¢</span>
          <h3 class="persona-title">U.S. Asset Holders</h3>
          <p class="persona-desc">Foreign families or HNWIs using Delaware C-Corp for U.S. real estate, operating businesses, or as blocker for estate tax planning (FIRPTA considerations apply).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="persona-card">
          <span class="persona-icon">üåü</span>
          <h3 class="persona-title">Accelerator Participants</h3>
          <p class="persona-desc">Non-U.S. founders accepted into Y Combinator, Techstars, or other U.S. accelerators. Programs typically require or strongly prefer Delaware C-Corp structure.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚ö†Ô∏è When Delaware C-Corp May Be Overkill</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">If you have <strong>no plans to raise institutional capital, no need for equity compensation, no U.S. employees, and minimal U.S. revenue</strong>, a Delaware C-Corp may add unnecessary complexity and cost. Consider:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ Delaware or Wyoming <strong>LLC</strong> for simpler structures<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Keeping your existing <strong>home-country entity</strong> if no U.S. presence needed<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Hybrid structure: foreign parent + U.S. subsidiary only when U.S. operations mature<br><br>
        Delaware C-Corp's advantages shine when <strong>fundraising, equity comp, or institutional partnerships</strong> are on the roadmap.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Formation Basics -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üìã</span>
        Delaware C-Corp Formation for Non-Residents: The Basics
      </h2>

      <h3>What You Need to Form:</h3>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>No U.S. citizenship or residency required</strong> for shareholders, directors, or officers‚Äîanyone globally can participate</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Registered agent in Delaware</strong> with physical street address ($50-300/year commercial service)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>EIN (Employer Identification Number)</strong> from IRS‚Äîrequired for banking; non-residents apply via mail/fax (4-8 week processing)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Bylaws & corporate resolutions</strong>‚Äîinternal governance documents for board meetings, stock issuance, officer appointments</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Stock certificates & ledger</strong>‚Äîdocumenting share ownership and equity structure</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Passport & proof of address</strong> for all shareholders 10%+‚Äîrequired for banking KYC compliance</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Formation & Annual Costs (2025):</h3>

      <div class="comparison-table-wrapper">
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Item</th>
              <th>Cost</th>
              <th>Frequency</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Delaware Certificate of Incorporation</td>
              <td>$89</td>
              <td>One-time</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Registered Agent Service</td>
              <td>$50-300</td>
              <td>Annual</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Delaware Annual Franchise Tax (10M shares)</td>
              <td>~$400</td>
              <td>Annual (due March 1)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>EIN Application</td>
              <td>FREE</td>
              <td>One-time</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Bylaws & Corporate Kit</td>
              <td>$0-800</td>
              <td>One-time</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>U.S. Corporate Tax Return (Form 1120)</td>
              <td>$1,000-5,000+</td>
              <td>Annual (CPA fees)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p><strong>First-year minimum:</strong> ~$500-1,000 (state fees + registered agent + legal docs). <strong>Annual recurring:</strong> ~$1,500-6,000+ (franchise tax + registered agent + CPA/tax compliance).</p>

      <div class="alert-box alert-info">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üí° C-Corp vs S-Corp for Non-Residents</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text"><strong>S-Corporations are NOT available</strong> if any shareholder is a non-resident alien. All non-resident-owned corporations default to <strong>C-Corporation</strong> tax treatment (double taxation: corporate tax + dividend withholding). This is non-negotiable under U.S. tax law.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Tax Obligations -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üíµ</span>
        U.S. Federal Tax Obligations: Corporate Level
      </h2>

      <p>This is where Delaware C-Corps differ fundamentally from LLCs for non-residents. Understanding corporate tax structure is critical.</p>

      <h3>1. Corporate Income Tax (Entity-Level)</h3>

      <p>Your Delaware C-Corporation is a <strong>U.S. tax resident</strong> under IRC ¬ß7701 (incorporated in the United States). This means:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Taxed on worldwide income</strong> at 21% federal corporate rate (current as of 2025)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Must file Form 1120</strong> (U.S. Corporation Income Tax Return) annually, regardless of profit/loss</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Can deduct ordinary business expenses</strong>‚Äîsalaries, contractors, software, marketing, rent, etc.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Quarterly estimated tax payments</strong> required if you owe $500+ in tax (Form 1120-W)</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p><strong>Key Insight:</strong> The <strong>corporation pays U.S. tax</strong>, not you personally (yet). You're shielded from direct U.S. income tax on corporate operating income‚Äîbut exposed via dividend withholding when profits are distributed.</p>

      <h3>2. Dividend Withholding to Foreign Shareholders</h3>

      <div class="alert-box alert-danger">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üö® 30% Withholding on Dividends</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">When your Delaware C-Corp distributes profits to you as dividends, the U.S. imposes a <strong>30% withholding tax</strong> on the gross dividend amount (no deductions). This is withheld at source by the corporation and remitted to the IRS.<br><br>
        <strong>Example:</strong> C-Corp distributes $100,000 dividend ‚Üí withholds $30,000 ‚Üí you receive $70,000.<br><br>
        <strong>Tax treaties can reduce this:</strong> Many countries have treaties reducing withholding to 15%, 5%, or even 0% depending on ownership % and treaty provisions. Check your country's U.S. tax treaty.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>3. Home Country Tax Implications</h3>

      <p>Your home country likely has rules for foreign corporate ownership:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>CFC (Controlled Foreign Corporation) rules:</strong> Many countries tax undistributed foreign corporate profits annually</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Worldwide income taxation:</strong> You may owe tax on dividends received in your home country</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Foreign tax credits:</strong> You can usually credit U.S. withholding tax against home-country tax liability</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Transfer pricing:</strong> If you have related-party transactions (e.g., foreign parent bills U.S. C-Corp for services), arm's-length pricing required</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚ö†Ô∏è Double Taxation Reality</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">C-Corp structure creates potential <strong>double (or triple) taxation</strong>:<br><br>
        1. U.S. corporate income tax (21%)<br>
        2. U.S. dividend withholding (30% or treaty rate)<br>
        3. Home country tax on dividends received<br><br>
        This is why <strong>tax planning BEFORE incorporation</strong> is critical. Strategies include: leaving profits in the corp, salary vs. dividend optimization, treaty planning, or hybrid structures. <strong>Work with cross-border CPAs/tax advisors.</strong></p>
      </div>

      <h3>4. When C-Corp Makes Sense Despite Double Tax</h3>

      <p>So why do non-residents still choose Delaware C-Corps? Because:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Venture capital requirement:</strong> VCs won't invest in LLCs or foreign entities‚ÄîC-Corp is non-negotiable</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Exit planning:</strong> M&A buyers and IPO markets expect C-Corp structure</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Equity compensation:</strong> Stock options (ISOs/NSOs) and equity grants only work in C-Corps</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Profit retention:</strong> If you reinvest profits (don't distribute), you only pay 21% corporate tax‚Äîno dividend withholding until distribution</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Credibility:</strong> U.S. enterprise customers, partners, and payment processors prefer corporate entities</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Banking & KYC -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üè¶</span>
        Banking & Payment Processors for Foreign-Owned C-Corps
      </h2>

      <p>Opening a U.S. bank account as a non-resident is challenging but achievable with the right approach and documentation.</p>

      <h3>Traditional U.S. Banks</h3>

      <p>Most traditional banks (Chase, Bank of America, Wells Fargo) require:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úó</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>In-person branch visit</strong> (not feasible for most international founders)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úó</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>U.S. Social Security Number (SSN)</strong> or ITIN for beneficial owners</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úó</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>U.S. address proof</strong> (utility bill, lease agreement)</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Traditional banks are generally <strong>not accessible</strong> for remote non-residents without SSN/ITIN.</p>

      <h3>Fintech & Neobanks (Better Options)</h3>

      <div class="comparison-table-wrapper">
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Platform</th>
              <th>Non-Resident Friendly?</th>
              <th>Key Requirements</th>
              <th>Best For</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Mercury</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Yes</td>
              <td>DE C-Corp, EIN, passport, business description, website</td>
              <td>Startups, SaaS, agencies</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Wise Business</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Yes</td>
              <td>Corp docs, EIN, passport, proof of address, verification call</td>
              <td>International transactions, multi-currency</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Relay</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Yes</td>
              <td>DE/WY corp, EIN, business plan or website</td>
              <td>Small businesses, multiple accounts</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Brex</strong></td>
              <td>‚ö†Ô∏è Selective</td>
              <td>VC-backed preferred, stricter underwriting</td>
              <td>Funded startups, high-growth companies</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Stripe Atlas Banking</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Yes (bundled)</td>
              <td>Forms DE C-Corp + opens account; $500 package</td>
              <td>Tech startups, first-time founders</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Payoneer</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Yes</td>
              <td>Corp docs, EIN, passport; limited banking features</td>
              <td>Receiving payments, cross-border transfers</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>What Documents Do Banks Require?</h3>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Certificate of Incorporation</strong> (stamped/filed by Delaware)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>EIN Confirmation Letter</strong> (IRS CP 575 or SS-4 approval)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Bylaws & Corporate Resolutions</strong> authorizing the bank account</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Passport for all shareholders 10%+</strong> and authorized signers</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Proof of address</strong> (utility bill, bank statement from home country)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Business documentation</strong>‚Äîwebsite, pitch deck, customer contracts, or product demo</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Business description & funding sources</strong>‚Äîwhere money comes from, what you do</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚ö†Ô∏è Bank Approval Is Not Guaranteed</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text"><strong>Having a Delaware C-Corp does not guarantee a bank account.</strong> Banks conduct risk-based underwriting. You may be denied if:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ Your country is on OFAC sanctions lists or high-risk jurisdictions<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Business model is high-risk (crypto, forex, gambling, adult content, fintech, remittances)<br>
        ‚Ä¢ No demonstrable business activity (no website, no customers, vague description)<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Incomplete KYC documentation or suspicious activity patterns<br><br>
        <strong>Best practice:</strong> Have a <strong>functioning business with real customers</strong> before incorporating. Banks want to see legitimate commercial activity, not shell companies.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Payment Processors (Stripe, PayPal, etc.)</h3>

      <p><strong>Stripe:</strong> Accepts foreign-owned Delaware C-Corps with U.S. bank account. Requires same KYC as banks. Popular for SaaS/online businesses.</p>

      <p><strong>PayPal Business:</strong> Accepts foreign-owned U.S. C-Corps, but may have transaction limits based on country of beneficial owner.</p>

      <p><strong>Square:</strong> Similar to Stripe; requires U.S. bank account and EIN. Good for e-commerce and retail.</p>

      <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Most payment processors accept foreign-owned C-Corps <strong>IF you have a U.S. business bank account</strong>. The bank account is the critical first step.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- C-Corp vs LLC Comparison -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">‚öñÔ∏è</span>
        Delaware C-Corp vs LLC for Non-Residents: Decision Matrix
      </h2>

      <p>When should you choose C-Corp over LLC (or vice versa)?</p>

      <div class="comparison-table-wrapper">
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Factor</th>
              <th class="highlight">Delaware C-Corp</th>
              <th>Delaware LLC</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Venture Capital</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Required by VCs</td>
              <td>‚ùå VCs won't invest</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Stock Options/Equity Comp</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Full support (ISOs, NSOs, RSUs)</td>
              <td>‚ö†Ô∏è Profit interests only (complex)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Taxation</strong></td>
              <td>21% corp tax + 30% dividend withholding</td>
              <td>Pass-through (complex for foreign owners)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>U.S. Tax Filings</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">Form 1120 (simpler for non-residents)</td>
              <td>Form 5472 + 1040-NR or 1065 (complex)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Profit Retention</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Can retain profits without distribution</td>
              <td>‚ùå Pass-through tax even if not distributed</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Investor Familiarity</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Standard, expected structure</td>
              <td>‚ö†Ô∏è Uncommon for institutional investors</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Annual Costs</strong></td>
              <td>~$1,500-6,000+ (tax, franchise, CPA)</td>
              <td>~$500-3,000+ (depends on structure)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Corporate Formalities</strong></td>
              <td>Board meetings, stock ledger, minutes</td>
              <td>Simpler (operating agreement flexibility)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Exit/M&A</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Preferred by acquirers</td>
              <td>‚ö†Ô∏è May require conversion pre-exit</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>IPO/Going Public</strong></td>
              <td class="highlight">‚úÖ Required structure</td>
              <td>‚ùå Must convert to C-Corp</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Choose Delaware C-Corp If:</h3>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Plan to raise institutional capital</strong> (VC, angels, accelerators)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Want to offer stock options</strong> to employees or advisors</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Building high-growth startup</strong> targeting acquisition or IPO</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Prefer simpler U.S. tax filing</strong> (Form 1120 vs LLC complexity for foreign owners)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Will reinvest profits</strong> (not distribute) for several years</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Choose Delaware LLC If:</h3>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>No plans for VC fundraising</strong> (bootstrapped or friends/family only)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Small service business</strong> (consulting, agency, freelancing)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Prefer flexible governance</strong> without corporate formalities</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Lower ongoing costs</strong> are priority</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Will distribute profits annually</strong> (and accept pass-through complexity)</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Common Pitfalls -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üö´</span>
        Common Mistakes & Misconceptions
      </h2>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">‚ùå</span>
              <span>"Delaware C-Corp means I don't pay U.S. tax"</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>FALSE.</strong> Your Delaware C-Corporation is a <strong>U.S. taxpayer</strong> subject to 21% federal corporate income tax on worldwide income. The corporation files Form 1120 and pays tax on profits. Additionally, when you take dividends, there's 30% withholding (or treaty rate). You absolutely pay U.S. tax‚Äîit's just at the corporate level first.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">‚ùå</span>
              <span>"I don't need to worry about my home country tax"</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>DANGEROUS.</strong> Most countries tax residents on worldwide income, including dividends from foreign corporations. Many have CFC (Controlled Foreign Corporation) rules that tax undistributed foreign corporate profits. You may face:<br><br>
            ‚Ä¢ Home country income tax on dividends received<br>
            ‚Ä¢ CFC taxation on retained earnings<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Transfer pricing audits if you have related-party transactions<br><br>
            <strong>Always consult a tax advisor in your home country</strong> before forming a U.S. C-Corp.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">‚ùå</span>
              <span>"Delaware corporations are anonymous"</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>PARTIALLY TRUE.</strong> Delaware does not publicly list shareholders or directors in its corporate registry. However:<br><br>
            ‚Ä¢ Banks and payment processors require full KYC on all beneficial owners 10%+<br>
            ‚Ä¢ IRS knows ownership via tax returns and Forms 5472 (if applicable)<br>
            ‚Ä¢ BOI rules (if they return) may require disclosure to FinCEN<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Legal discovery, subpoenas, or court orders can pierce anonymity<br><br>
            You have <strong>privacy from casual public searches</strong>, not <strong>anonymity from authorities or counterparties</strong>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">‚ùå</span>
              <span>"U.S. bank account approval is automatic with a C-Corp"</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>FALSE.</strong> Bank approval is discretionary and risk-based. Many non-residents are denied even with valid C-Corps. To maximize approval chances:<br><br>
            ‚Ä¢ Have a functioning business with real customers/revenue<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Provide complete KYC documentation (passports, proof of address, corporate docs)<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Your country must not be on OFAC sanctions lists<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Business model must be acceptable to bank's risk appetite<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Consider multiple banks/fintechs in parallel</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">‚ùå</span>
              <span>"I can treat corporate funds as personal money"</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>TERRIBLE IDEA.</strong> Corporations are separate legal entities. Mixing personal and corporate funds ("piercing the corporate veil") can:<br><br>
            ‚Ä¢ Destroy limited liability protection<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Trigger tax problems (constructive dividends, loans to shareholders)<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Kill M&A deals during due diligence<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Create accounting nightmares<br><br>
            Maintain strict separation: corporate bank account, proper documentation, board resolutions for major decisions, arm's-length transactions.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">‚ùå</span>
              <span>"I'll figure out taxes after incorporation"</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>BACKWARDS.</strong> Tax structure should drive incorporation decisions, not the other way around. Once the C-Corp exists:<br><br>
            ‚Ä¢ You're locked into double taxation (corporate + dividend withholding)<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Annual filing obligations begin immediately<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Dissolving retroactively doesn't erase past filing requirements<br>
            ‚Ä¢ Restructuring later is expensive and complex<br><br>
            <strong>Get tax advice BEFORE forming.</strong> Sometimes a hybrid structure (foreign parent + U.S. subsidiary, or LLC taxed as C-Corp) is better for your specific situation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Corporate Formalities & Governance -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üìä</span>
        Corporate Formalities & Governance for Foreign Founders
      </h2>

      <p>Delaware C-Corporations require ongoing corporate governance that differs significantly from LLCs or foreign entity structures. Understanding these requirements prevents legal problems and maintains limited liability protection.</p>

      <h3>Required Corporate Records & Documentation</h3>

      <div class="process-timeline">
        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">1</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Certificate of Incorporation</div>
            <div class="process-desc">Filed with Delaware; defines authorized shares, par value (if any), corporate name, registered agent, and any special provisions (like PBC status or preferred stock classes). This is your corporate charter‚Äîamendment requires board + shareholder approval.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">2</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Bylaws</div>
            <div class="process-desc">Internal rules governing board meetings, shareholder meetings, officer roles, quorum requirements, voting procedures. Not filed publicly but legally binding. Can be amended by board (unless charter reserves to shareholders).</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">3</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Stock Ledger & Certificates</div>
            <div class="process-desc">Legal record of all stock issuances, transfers, cancellations. Must track: shareholder name, address, certificate number, shares owned, date issued. Physical or electronic certificates. Required for tax compliance and M&A due diligence.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">4</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Board Meeting Minutes</div>
            <div class="process-desc">Written record of board decisions: stock issuances, officer appointments, major contracts, fundraising approvals, dividend declarations. Even single-director corps should document decisions via written consent or minutes.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">5</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Shareholder Meeting Minutes/Consents</div>
            <div class="process-desc">Annual shareholder meetings required (or written consents in lieu). Must elect directors, approve major changes (charter amendments, mergers, dissolutions). Document everything‚Äîcourts can pierce veil if formalities ignored.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">6</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Stock Purchase Agreements</div>
            <div class="process-desc">Contracts governing founder stock (vesting, repurchase rights, transfer restrictions). Investor stock purchases governed by term sheets and stock purchase agreements. ALWAYS use written agreements‚Äîoral promises are litigation disasters.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Board of Directors: Structure & Responsibilities</h3>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Minimum 1 director required</strong> in Delaware (most states require 1-3). Can have sole director even with multiple shareholders. As you add investors, expect 3-7 director board with investor seats.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Directors don't need to be shareholders</strong>‚Äîcan appoint outside advisors, investors, or independent directors. Non-resident directors are fine; no U.S. citizenship/residency required.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Board manages the corporation</strong>‚Äînot shareholders. Day-to-day decisions by officers (CEO, CFO), but major decisions require board approval: fundraising, M&A, stock issuances, significant contracts, amendments.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Fiduciary duties:</strong> Directors owe duties of care and loyalty to the corporation and shareholders. Must act in good faith, inform themselves, avoid conflicts of interest. Delaware courts strictly enforce these.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Regular meetings recommended</strong>‚Äîquarterly is standard for active startups. Can meet virtually (Zoom, etc.). Document attendance, discussions, and votes in minutes. Use board resolutions for major actions.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Officers & Management</h3>

      <p>Delaware law is flexible on officer titles, but typical structure:</p>

      <div class="comparison-table-wrapper">
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Officer Title</th>
              <th>Typical Responsibilities</th>
              <th>Required?</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>President/CEO</strong></td>
              <td>Day-to-day operations, execute contracts, manage employees, report to board</td>
              <td class="highlight">Usually Required</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Secretary</strong></td>
              <td>Maintain corporate records, meeting minutes, stock ledger, file annual reports</td>
              <td class="highlight">Often Required</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Treasurer/CFO</strong></td>
              <td>Financial management, tax compliance, fundraising, investor relations</td>
              <td>Optional (recommended)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Vice President</strong></td>
              <td>Varies‚ÄîVP Engineering, VP Sales, etc. Delegated authority for specific areas</td>
              <td>Optional</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-info">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üí° One Person Can Hold Multiple Roles</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">Delaware allows one person to be sole shareholder, sole director, and all officers simultaneously. Common for early-stage solo founders. As you grow, separate roles for governance, accountability, and investor confidence. VCs typically require multi-person board and separation of board/management roles.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Annual Compliance Calendar</h3>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">üìÖ</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>March 1:</strong> Delaware annual franchise tax due (~$400 for typical startup with 10M authorized shares). Late fees accrue. Pay online via Delaware Division of Corporations portal.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">üìÖ</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>March 15 (or month 3 + 15 days after fiscal year-end):</strong> U.S. Corporate Tax Return (Form 1120) due. File even if no profit/loss. Extensions available but don't extend payment deadline if tax owed.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">üìÖ</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Quarterly (if tax owed):</strong> Estimated corporate tax payments (Form 1120-W) if you expect to owe $500+ in tax. Penalties for underpayment.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">üìÖ</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Annually:</strong> Shareholder meeting (or written consent in lieu) to elect directors. Document in minutes. Required by Delaware law even for single-shareholder corps.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">üìÖ</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>As needed:</strong> Board meetings/consents for stock issuances, option grants, major contracts, fundraising rounds. Quarterly board meetings recommended for active startups.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚ö†Ô∏è Piercing the Corporate Veil</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">If you ignore corporate formalities‚Äîno minutes, commingling funds, treating corp as alter ego‚Äîcourts can "pierce the corporate veil" and hold shareholders personally liable for corporate debts. This is especially risky for foreign founders who may not understand U.S. corporate law requirements. <strong>Maintain formalities religiously</strong>: separate bank account, document major decisions, annual meetings, arm's-length dealings.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Stock Options & Equity Compensation -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üíé</span>
        Stock Options & Equity Compensation: Deep Dive
      </h2>

      <p>One of the primary reasons non-resident founders choose Delaware C-Corps over LLCs is the ability to offer stock-based compensation to employees, advisors, and contractors. This is critical for attracting U.S. talent and scaling globally.</p>

      <h3>Types of Equity Compensation</h3>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">üìà</span>
              <span>Incentive Stock Options (ISOs)</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Who can receive:</strong> U.S. employees only (not contractors or non-employees). Foreign employees don't qualify for ISOs.</p>

            <p><strong>Tax advantage:</strong> If held 2+ years from grant and 1+ year from exercise, gains taxed as long-term capital gains (lower rate than ordinary income) rather than ordinary income.</p>

            <p><strong>Limits:</strong> $100,000 worth (at grant FMV) can vest per employee per year. Excess treated as NSOs.</p>

            <p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Employee pays exercise price (usually $0.01-1.00/share for early employees). No tax at exercise (but AMT can apply). Tax due when shares sold.</p>

            <p><strong>Requirements:</strong> Must be granted at fair market value (409A valuation required). Expire 10 years from grant (or 90 days post-termination unless extended).</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">üåç</span>
              <span>Non-Qualified Stock Options (NSOs)</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Who can receive:</strong> Anyone‚Äîemployees (U.S. or foreign), contractors, advisors, directors, consultants.</p>

            <p><strong>Tax treatment:</strong> Spread between exercise price and FMV at exercise is taxed as ordinary income immediately upon exercise (even if shares not sold). Then capital gains on appreciation from exercise to sale.</p>

            <p><strong>Flexibility:</strong> Can be granted below FMV (though uncommon). Can have extended post-termination exercise periods. Preferred for non-U.S. employees and contractors.</p>

            <p><strong>Withholding:</strong> For U.S. employees, company must withhold income tax + payroll tax at exercise. For foreign contractors, may need to issue 1099 or navigate foreign tax withholding.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">üéÅ</span>
              <span>Restricted Stock Units (RSUs)</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>What they are:</strong> Promise to deliver stock in the future upon vesting. No upfront payment required. Common at late-stage startups and public companies.</p>

            <p><strong>Tax treatment:</strong> Full FMV at vesting taxed as ordinary income. Withholding applies. Then capital gains on appreciation post-vesting.</p>

            <p><strong>Advantages:</strong> No exercise price (recipient gets shares for free upon vesting). No AMT issues. Simple to administer.</p>

            <p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong> Ordinary income tax on full value at vesting (can be large if company valuable). Less favorable than ISOs for employees.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">‚≠ê</span>
              <span>Restricted Stock Awards (RSAs) & 83(b) Elections</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>What they are:</strong> Actual stock issued upfront, subject to vesting/repurchase. Founder stock is typically RSA with vesting.</p>

            <p><strong>Tax treatment (without 83(b)):</strong> Taxed as ordinary income at FMV on each vesting date. Disaster if company value increases‚Äîyou owe tax on unvested shares.</p>

            <p><strong>83(b) Election:</strong> File with IRS within 30 days of grant, pay tax on FMV at grant (often $0 or minimal for founders). Then ALL future appreciation is capital gains, no tax at vesting.</p>

            <p><strong>CRITICAL for founders:</strong> Every Delaware C-Corp founder receiving restricted stock with vesting MUST file 83(b) election within 30 days. Miss the deadline = massive tax bill later. Not recoverable.</p>

            <p><strong>Example:</strong> Founder receives 2M shares at $0.001/share FMV, 4-year vesting. Files 83(b), pays tax on $2,000 value. Four years later, company worth $10M, founder's shares worth $5M. No tax at vesting‚Äîonly capital gains when sold. Without 83(b)? Ordinary income tax on $5M over 4 years.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Equity Incentive Plan (ESOP) Setup</h3>

      <p>Before granting options, you need a formal equity incentive plan approved by board and shareholders:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Pool size:</strong> Typically 10-20% of post-money capitalization reserved for employee options. VCs will expect this. Create the pool BEFORE VC financing to avoid dilution to founders.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Board administration:</strong> Plan administered by board (or compensation committee). Board approves each grant, exercise price, vesting schedule.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Standard vesting:</strong> 4 years with 1-year cliff is market standard. Means nothing vests for first year; then 25% vests at 1 year; then monthly/quarterly thereafter. Protects company if employee leaves early.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Exercise price = FMV:</strong> Options must be granted at fair market value per IRC ¬ß409A. Requires 409A valuation ($2K-5K from qualified firm). Update annually or after major events (fundraising, etc.).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Post-termination exercise:</strong> Standard is 90 days after termination to exercise vested options or they expire. Some plans allow extensions (especially for foreign employees who need time to arrange payment/taxes).</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>409A Valuations: The IRS Requirement</h3>

      <div class="alert-box alert-danger">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üö® 409A Compliance Is Mandatory</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">IRC ¬ß409A requires stock options to be granted at "fair market value" or face massive penalties (20% penalty tax + interest on recipient). For C-Corps, you MUST obtain an independent 409A valuation before granting options.<br><br>
        <strong>Cost:</strong> $2,000-5,000 from specialized firms (Carta, AngelList, Pulley, etc.).<br>
        <strong>Frequency:</strong> At least annually, and after "material events" (fundraising rounds, major revenue changes, acquisitions, etc.).<br>
        <strong>Safe harbor:</strong> IRS gives "presumption of reasonableness" to independent 409A valuations, protecting you from penalties.<br><br>
        DIY or "back of envelope" valuations DO NOT qualify. Get a professional 409A. Budget this as recurring annual expense ($3K-7K/year as company grows).</p>
      </div>

      <h3>International Employees & Stock Compensation</h3>

      <p>If you're a non-resident founder planning to hire team members in your home country or other countries:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>ISOs don't work:</strong> Only for U.S. employees. Grant NSOs to foreign employees instead.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Home country tax:</strong> Foreign employees typically owe tax in their country on option exercise and sale. Tax treatment varies by country. Consult local advisors.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Withholding complexity:</strong> Some countries require employer withholding on stock comp. U.S. C-Corp may not have infrastructure to withhold foreign taxes. Often structured as contractor grants (not employee) to avoid this.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Securities law:</strong> Offering equity to foreign persons can trigger securities registration in those countries. Use exemptions (employee plans usually exempt) or restrict grants to U.S. residents only.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Best practice:</strong> Use specialized global equity platforms (Carta, Pulley, Shareworks) that handle multi-country equity grants, tax forms, and compliance.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Cross-Border Structuring -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üåç</span>
        Cross-Border Structuring: Foreign Parent vs. U.S. Parent
      </h2>

      <p>Non-resident founders often face a critical structural question: Should the Delaware C-Corp be the parent entity, or should your foreign company be the parent with the U.S. C-Corp as a subsidiary?</p>

      <h3>Three Common Structures</h3>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">üá∫üá∏</span>
              <span>Structure 1: Delaware C-Corp as Parent (No Foreign Entity)</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Structure:</strong> Founders directly own Delaware C-Corp. No foreign entity. All operations run through U.S. corporation.</p>

            <p><strong>When to use:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>You don't have an existing foreign company</li>
              <li>Most/all customers and operations are in the U.S.</li>
              <li>Raising U.S. VC is primary near-term goal</li>
              <li>Founders willing to operate purely as U.S. entity</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Simplest structure‚Äîonly one entity to maintain</li>
              <li>Lower cost (only U.S. compliance, no dual-entity overhead)</li>
              <li>Cleanest for VCs (they own direct equity in operating company)</li>
              <li>No transfer pricing or inter-company complexity</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>All profit subject to 21% U.S. corporate tax first</li>
              <li>Dividends to foreign founders face 30% withholding (or treaty rate)</li>
              <li>If operations are primarily in home country, U.S. C-Corp may create inefficient tax structure</li>
              <li>No foreign entity for local market credibility if needed</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">üåç</span>
              <span>Structure 2: Foreign Parent ‚Üí Delaware C-Corp Subsidiary</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Structure:</strong> You (founders) own foreign company (UK Ltd, German GmbH, Singapore PTE, etc.). Foreign company owns 100% of Delaware C-Corp as U.S. subsidiary.</p>

            <p><strong>When to use:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>You already have established foreign business</li>
              <li>Most operations/employees are in home country</li>
              <li>U.S. subsidiary primarily for sales, distribution, or market presence</li>
              <li>Home country has favorable IP or holding company tax regime</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Keeps foreign operations in foreign entity (may have lower tax rates)</li>
              <li>Intellectual property can be owned by foreign parent, licensed to U.S. sub</li>
              <li>Foreign parent can have different shareholders than U.S. sub if needed</li>
              <li>Dividends from U.S. sub to foreign parent may qualify for treaty benefits</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>U.S. VCs don't like this‚Äîthey want direct equity in U.S. operating company, not foreign parent</li>
              <li>Requires "flip" to U.S. parent before fundraising (expensive, complex)</li>
              <li>Transfer pricing required for inter-company transactions (legal, accounting costs)</li>
              <li>Two entities = double the compliance, audits, tax filings, costs</li>
              <li>CFC (Controlled Foreign Corporation) rules in home country may tax U.S. sub profits immediately</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
          <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
            <div class="accordion-title">
              <span class="icon">üîÑ</span>
              <span>Structure 3: Delaware C-Corp Parent ‚Üí Foreign Subsidiary</span>
            </div>
            <span class="accordion-toggle">‚ñº</span>
          </div>
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Structure:</strong> Founders directly own Delaware C-Corp (parent). Delaware C-Corp owns foreign subsidiary in home country for local operations/employees.</p>

            <p><strong>When to use:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Planning to raise U.S. VC (they require U.S. parent)</li>
              <li>Need legal presence in home country for employees, contracts, or regulatory reasons</li>
              <li>Want clean cap table for investors (all equity in U.S. entity)</li>
              <li>Eventual exit likely to U.S. or global acquirer</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>VC-friendly structure (investors own parent, control everything)</li>
              <li>Can hire employees in home country through local subsidiary (payroll, benefits, compliance easier)</li>
              <li>Foreign subsidiary can be simple entity (no need for complex corp structure)</li>
              <li>Parent controls all IP, subsidiaries are service/ops entities</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>All profit ultimately flows to U.S. parent (U.S. tax at 21%)</li>
              <li>Transfer pricing still required (U.S. parent pays subsidiary for services at arm's length)</li>
              <li>Foreign subsidiary profits may be taxed twice (local + U.S. repatriation) unless treaty relief</li>
              <li>Complexity and cost of maintaining dual entities</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-info">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üí° The "Standard" VC-Backed Structure</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">For startups planning to raise U.S. venture capital, <strong>Structure 3</strong> (Delaware C-Corp parent ‚Üí foreign subsidiaries) is the market standard. VCs won't invest in foreign parents or U.S. subsidiaries. They want:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ Direct equity ownership in the U.S. C-Corp parent<br>
        ‚Ä¢ U.S. parent owns all IP and controls all subsidiaries<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Clean cap table with all investors at parent level<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Subsidiaries are "cost centers" (R&D, sales offices) not separate equity structures<br><br>
        If you start with Structure 2 (foreign parent), you'll need to "flip" to Structure 3 before raising VC‚Äîa complex, expensive restructuring. <strong>Better to start with Structure 3 if fundraising is on the roadmap.</strong></p>
      </div>

      <h3>Transfer Pricing Basics</h3>

      <p>When you have related entities (parent-subsidiary, or sister companies under common ownership), transactions between them must be at "arm's length"‚Äîmeaning market rates, as if dealing with unrelated parties.</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>What triggers transfer pricing:</strong> Intercompany services, IP licensing, management fees, cost allocations, loans, goods sold between entities. Anytime money or value moves between related entities across borders.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Arm's length standard:</strong> IRS (and foreign tax authorities) require intercompany pricing to match what independent parties would charge. Can't artificially shift profits to low-tax jurisdictions.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Documentation required:</strong> Transfer pricing studies, intercompany agreements, invoices showing calculations. Cost: $5K-50K+ depending on complexity. Required for audits.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Common methods:</strong> Cost-plus (services), comparable uncontrolled price (goods), profit split (joint value creation). Tax advisors help determine appropriate method.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚ö†Ô∏è</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Penalties for errors:</strong> Both countries can adjust pricing and assess additional tax + penalties. Can result in double taxation if both countries claim the profits. Transfer pricing disputes are expensive.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚ö†Ô∏è Transfer Pricing Is Complex‚ÄîGet Help</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">Transfer pricing is one of the most complex areas of international tax. If you have cross-border group structures, budget $10K-50K+ annually for transfer pricing studies, documentation, and tax advisory. DIY transfer pricing invites audits and double taxation. Work with CPAs/tax advisors experienced in international transfer pricing from day one.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- The Flip -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üîÑ</span>
        The "Flip": Converting from Foreign Entity to Delaware C-Corp
      </h2>

      <p>Many non-resident founders start with a foreign company (home-country entity), build traction, then need to "flip" to a Delaware C-Corp structure to raise U.S. venture capital. This is a complex, expensive process‚Äîunderstanding it upfront helps you plan better.</p>

      <h3>Why the Flip Is Necessary</h3>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>VC requirement:</strong> U.S. venture capital funds have legal/tax restrictions preventing investment in foreign entities. Their LPAs (limited partnership agreements) require U.S. C-Corp investments.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Stock option plans:</strong> Foreign entities can't easily offer U.S.-style stock options/RSUs. VCs expect option pools for hiring.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Exit preference:</strong> Acquirers (especially U.S. tech companies) strongly prefer acquiring Delaware C-Corps. M&A involving foreign targets is more complex/expensive.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">‚úì</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Cap table clarity:</strong> Delaware law and market conventions around preferred stock, liquidation preferences, drag-along rights, etc. are well-established. Foreign entities lack this.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Common Flip Structures</h3>

      <div class="process-timeline">
        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">1</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Share Exchange / Stock-for-Stock Swap</div>
            <div class="process-desc"><strong>How it works:</strong> Form new Delaware C-Corp. Foreign company shareholders exchange their foreign shares for new Delaware C-Corp shares. Foreign company becomes wholly-owned subsidiary of Delaware C-Corp (or is dissolved).<br><br>
            <strong>Tax:</strong> Can often be structured as tax-free reorganization under IRC ¬ß368 if done correctly. Requires careful planning.<br><br>
            <strong>Cost:</strong> $15K-50K+ in legal/tax fees. Complex documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">2</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Asset Transfer</div>
            <div class="process-desc"><strong>How it works:</strong> Form Delaware C-Corp. Foreign company transfers assets (IP, contracts, tech, goodwill) to Delaware C-Corp in exchange for stock. Foreign company liquidates or becomes passive holding company.<br><br>
            <strong>Tax:</strong> Can trigger recognition of gains on asset transfers in both U.S. and home country. Complex to structure as tax-free. Often requires home-country tax clearance.<br><br>
            <strong>Cost:</strong> $20K-75K+ in legal/tax/accounting fees. Transfer tax, VAT, or stamp duties may apply depending on jurisdiction.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="process-step">
          <div class="process-number">3</div>
          <div class="process-content">
            <div class="process-title">Fresh Start (Wind Down Foreign, Start Fresh)</div>
            <div class="process-desc"><strong>How it works:</strong> Close foreign company (or let it go dormant). Founders form new Delaware C-Corp. Assign/transfer key assets informally. Treat as new start.<br><br>
            <strong>Tax:</strong> Simplest tax treatment but may trigger liquidation tax in home country. Loss of historical corporate value/continuity.<br><br>
            <strong>Cost:</strong> Lowest cost ($5K-15K), but loses corporate history, existing contracts stay with foreign entity (need to novate/re-sign), potential disruption to customers/partners.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Timing Considerations</h3>

      <div class="alert-box alert-success">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚úÖ Best Time to Flip</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text"><strong>Before significant revenue or complex cap tables.</strong> Ideal timing:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ Pre-revenue or early revenue (<$500K ARR)<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Simple cap table (founders only, maybe 1-2 angels)<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Before hiring many employees in foreign entity<br>
        ‚Ä¢ 6-12 months before planned VC fundraise<br><br>
        Flipping a $5M ARR company with 20 employees, complex IP, and multiple investors? Expect $50K-150K+ in legal/tax fees and 3-6 months of work. <strong>Flip early if you know you'll need to flip eventually.</strong></p>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-danger">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üö® Worst Time to Flip</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">Do NOT flip:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ During active fundraising (VCs won't wait 3-6 months)<br>
        ‚Ä¢ With complex multi-country operations and employees already in place<br>
        ‚Ä¢ If you have outstanding foreign tax or regulatory issues<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Right before a planned acquisition (flip can complicate M&A)<br><br>
        Plan flip well in advance of fundraising. VCs can sometimes bridge with convertible notes while flip completes, but it's not ideal.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Alternative: Start as Delaware C-Corp from Day One</h3>

      <p>If you're confident you'll eventually raise U.S. VC or target a U.S. exit, consider starting as a Delaware C-Corp immediately‚Äîeven as a non-resident founder. Avoids the flip entirely. Use foreign subsidiaries for local operations/employees as needed. This is increasingly common for international SaaS founders.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Decision Framework -->
    <div class="section-card">
      <h2 class="section-title">
        <span class="icon">üéØ</span>
        Decision Framework: Should YOU Form a Delaware C-Corp?
      </h2>

      <p>Answer these questions to determine if Delaware C-Corp is right for your situation:</p>

      <div class="feature-list">
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">?</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Do you plan to raise venture capital or angel investment in the next 2-3 years?</strong><br>If YES ‚Üí Delaware C-Corp strongly recommended. If NO ‚Üí LLC or foreign entity may suffice.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">?</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Will you need to offer stock options or equity compensation?</strong><br>If YES ‚Üí C-Corp required for proper equity comp. If NO ‚Üí LLC profit interests work but are complex.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">?</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Can you afford $2,000-6,000+/year in ongoing compliance costs?</strong><br>If NO ‚Üí Reconsider timing or choose simpler structure. If YES ‚Üí C-Corp is sustainable.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">?</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Do you have U.S. customers, revenue, or business operations?</strong><br>If NO ‚Üí Consider waiting until U.S. presence is established. If YES ‚Üí C-Corp makes sense.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">?</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Are you willing to manage corporate formalities (board meetings, minutes, stock ledger)?</strong><br>If NO ‚Üí LLC is simpler. If YES ‚Üí C-Corp governance is manageable.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">?</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Can you qualify for U.S. banking (fintech or traditional)?</strong><br>If NO (sanctions country, high-risk business) ‚Üí Major obstacle. If YES ‚Üí Proceed with confidence.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-item">
          <div class="feature-check">?</div>
          <div class="feature-text"><strong>Have you consulted with both U.S. and home-country tax advisors?</strong><br>If NO ‚Üí Stop and get advice first. If YES ‚Üí You understand the tax implications.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-success">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚úÖ Green Light Scenario</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">Delaware C-Corp is likely the right choice if:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ Building high-growth tech/SaaS startup targeting VC funding<br>
        ‚Ä¢ U.S. is primary market or future market<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Need to hire U.S. employees or grant equity comp<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Plan to reinvest profits for 3-5+ years (minimize dividend withholding)<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Can afford professional legal/tax support ($3K-10K+ setup + ongoing compliance)</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
        <div class="alert-box-title">‚ö†Ô∏è Yellow Light‚ÄîProceed with Caution</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">Consider Delaware C-Corp but explore alternatives if:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ Early-stage, pre-product or pre-revenue<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Unsure about fundraising plans<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Limited U.S. connections today<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Budget-conscious (high setup/compliance costs are a strain)<br><br>
        <strong>Alternative:</strong> Start with home-country entity or Delaware LLC, flip to C-Corp later when fundraising/hiring needs are clear.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="alert-box alert-danger">
        <div class="alert-box-title">üö® Red Light‚ÄîDon't Do It (or Get Expert Help)</div>
        <p class="alert-box-text">Skip Delaware C-Corp or delay if:<br><br>
        ‚Ä¢ No U.S. customers, revenue, or business activities<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Can't open U.S. bank account (sanctions country, high-risk business model)<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Unwilling to manage corporate compliance and tax filings<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Business model is crypto, forex, gambling, or other banking-unfriendly categories<br>
        ‚Ä¢ Haven't consulted cross-border tax advisors (risk of catastrophic tax mistakes)</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

